title: Woman in front of bush, ca. 1919
"R.V. Brown Bear," June 1954
description: The Brown Bear was built in 1934 with funds from the Works Progress Administration. It was used by the U.S. Bureau of Biological Survey and the Alaska Game Commission for biological research excursion to Alaska. It was used during the U.S. Navy during World War II and acquired by the University of Washington Department of Oceanography in 1952.

title: Two men demonstrating W.F. Young's Bolting-Up Jack at Puget Sound Navy Yard, 1919
description: According to an article in International Marine Engineering, Volume 25 (available through Google Books) the jack was designed by W.F. Young, an employee at the Puget Sound Navy Yard to help construct ships more efficiently. The article includes diagrams of the tool and describes its uses.

title: Man with Materials Reclamation Co. truck, ca. 1950
description: The 1948 City Directory lists the company at 911 Western Ave with Thomas O'Brube as the manager. The plant is listed at 1102 W. Hanford. The company is listed in the 1951 City Directory at 4201 W. Marginal Way. Thomas O'Burke and J.F. Thompson are listed as the proprietors.

title: Cornish Follies, 1929
description: The Follies were a revue group from Cornish College offering skits, dances, songs and other entertainment.
subjects: Cornish College of Allied Arts (Seattle, Wash.)--Students

title: Andrew Bahr, wife and Frances Brown in New Washington Hotel, April 3, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1511 ANDREW BAHR WILL SPEND FIRST VACATION IN FIVE YEARS AS COMMITTEEMAN OF THE NATIONAL TOURNAMENT AND OLYMPIC TRIALS. Seattle, Washington. - When a sailor gets his vacation he usually takes his best girl rowing on the park lake and just so a San Francisco police reported who had not had a relief from his boat in ten years took a vacation riding on the hurry-up wagon. Well Andrew Bahr, the great herder is going to follow along the same lines. His vacation has started and he is going to Mt. Rainier in a few days to supervise the running of the National Olympic trials which start next week. Photo shows Miss Frances Brown pinning the emblem of the Knights of the Skis. Direct Service .... 4/3/1935 ....."

title: Seattle-Tacoma Airport, ca. 1950
description: The Seattle-Tacoma Airport was constructed in 1944 by the Port of Seattle.

Men at Puget Sound Navy Yard with W.F. Young's Bolting-Up Jack, 1919

title: Reindeer at Woodland Park, March 7, 1898
description: Transcribed from photograph: "9066 - Government Reindeer en route for Alaska, Woodland Park, Seattle, Wash., U.S.A. Copyright 1898 by B.L. Lingley. The reindeer, originally from Norway, were being shipped to Alaska to serve as pack animals for Alaskan gold seekers."

title: Cornish Follies, 1929
description: The Follies were a revue group from Cornish College offering skits, dances, songs and other entertainment. Individuals pictured, from left to right, are: Bernice Encretson, Beth Williams, Richard Odlin, Bethene Miller and Dorothy Fisher.
subjects: Cornish College of Allied Arts (Seattle, Wash.)--Students

title: Men aboard seaplane at Sand Point Naval Station, July 21, 1934
description: Transcribed from newspaper caption on back of photograph: "Watch your credit line: Photo from Wide World Photos: SEA: 1033 Six Navy Planes arrive in Seattle on Alaska flight. Seattle Washington. - Six of Uncle Sam's crack flying squadron were moored today after a flight from Southern California in what will be the first mass formation of a fleet of twelve planes to fly to that region. The flight purpose will be of great significance, as in defense of the Pacific Northwest. Photo shows officers and crew of the 7-P-I as they were being docked at Sand Point Seattle. Direct service ..... 7/21/34...."

title: Woman and rose bush, ca. 1919
Norman Knudsen at Music Hall Theatre organ, ca. 1930
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Mr. Norman Knudsen at Music Hall Theater organ four-manual. Seattle, Wash." The Music Hall Theatre (also known as the Fox Theater) opened in 1929. It was demolished in 1992.

title: Andrew Bahr and wife in New Washington Hotel after arctic trek, April 3, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1510 AFTER FIVE YEARS IN ARCTIC, ANDY BAHR HAS FIRST BREAKFAST WITH THE MISSES."

title: Steam shovel regrading 3rd Ave. near James St., 1907
description: Transcribed from photograph: "9865 - Cutting down a street with a steam-shovel, - Seattle, Washington. Copyright 1907 Underwood & Underwood." Hotel Mansfield, located at 3rd Ave. and James St. is visible in the upper right corner of the photograph.

title: View east from 14th Ave. S. and S. Jackson St., 1927
intersection: 14th Ave. S. and S. Jackson St.

title: Children watching television, 1958
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Children viewing a Three Little Bruins film at home of Charles N. King. 1958." The 1958 City Directory lists Charles N. and Jeanette King at 9103 35th Ave. NE. Charles is listed as an engineer at Boeing.

title: Man and woman in canoe off of Alki Point, July 13, 1919
Exchange Building, ca. 1935
description: The Exchange Building was constructed between 1929 and 1930.

title: 2nd Ave. north from James St., ca. 1915
description: The Butler Hotel (completed 1890), Bailey Block (completed 1892) and Hoge Building (completed in 1911) appear on the left side of the street. The Crown Building, Oriental Block (completed 1903 and Alaska Building (completed 1904) appear on the right.

title: 1st Ave. south from Virginia St., June 22, 1971
description: The 1970 City Directory lists the Salvation Army (right) at 1929 1st Ave. and the English Furniture Company (left) at 1911 1st Ave.  Signs for Bob's Tavern (1905 1st Ave.) and the Fairmount Hotel (1907 1st Ave.) can also be seen at the far left. The Smith Block Building appears to the left of the Salvation Army, followed by the Butterworth Building, Alaska Trade Building and the Fairmount Apartments and Jones Building.
subjects: Fairmount Apartments and Jones Building (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Henry Sharf working on taxidermied goose at Jonas Brothers, February 12, 1961
description: Transcribed from newspaper caption on back of photograph: "Henry Sharf, an artist at his work, put the finishing touches on a mounted snow goose." The 1961-1962 Seattle City Directory lists the company at 1533 Boylston Ave.

title: Men at Puget Sound Navy Yard disassembling W.F. Young's Bolting-Up Jack, April 14, 1919
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Navy Yard, Puget Sound, April 15, 1919. W.F. Young's Bolting up Jack disassembled. Time required to disassemble, about one minute." According to an article in International Marine Engineering, Volume 25 (which features this photograph and is available through Google Books) the jack was designed by W.F. Young, an employee at the Puget Sound Navy Yard to help construct ships more efficiently. The article includes diagrams of the tool and describes its uses.

title: Guy Jonas combing fur on taxidermied bear, ca. 1949
description: The 1948-49 City Directory lists the Jonas Brothers taxidermy company at 1708 Broadway.

description: The Follies were a revue group from Cornish College offering skits, dances, songs and other entertainment.
subjects: Cornish College of Allied Arts (Seattle, Wash.)--Students

title: Woman standing near "Seattle Welcomes You" sign, ca. 1955
Sitting room aboard ""George Luckenbach,"" ca. 1955
description: The George Luckenbach (originally known as the S.S. Sea Star) was built in 1943 for the United States Maritime Commission. It was renamed during its service for the Luckenbach Steamship Company between 1948 and 1960. In 1960 the ship was sold to States Marine Lines and renamed Buckeye State. It was scrapped in 1973.

title: Aerial view of downtown Seattle from near 5th Ave. and Pike St., 1931
description: Photograph shows the view NW towards buildings such as the Seaboard Building, the Century Building the Bon Marche and the New Washington Hotel.

title: Smith Cannery Machines Company, ca. 1915
description: The company was located at 2413 1st Ave. S. They were responsible for producing the "Iron Chink" which removed salmon heads, tails and fins before splitting the fish in half.

title: Wrecked car being pulled from Lake Washington, May 12, 1955
description: Transcribed from photograph: "ARP - 051201 - 5/12/55 - SEATTLE: Body of Everett Chartrant sprawls on seat of his car as wreckers pull it from Lake Washington here (5/12). Chartrant traveling at ""east 90 miles per hour"" according to witnesses, struck bridge's draw span abutment and skidded and flew more than 120 feet to land on far side of well. (5/11). The car sank in 70 feet of water. Two US Navy Divers fastened cables to car so it could be hoisted from the water. UNITED PRESS TELEPHOTO."

title: Brown Bear cartoon, August 15, 1955
description: Transcribed from back of photograph: "Cartoon of Brown Bear (holding Nasen bottle equipped with Reversing Thermometers and a bathy thermograph). Drawn by Art Welch, 25 August 1955." The Brown Bear was built in 1934 with funds from the Works Progress Administration. It was used by the U.S. Bureau of Biological Survey and the Alaska Game Commission for biological research excursion to Alaska. It was used during the U.S. Navy during World War II and acquired by the University of Washington Department of Oceanography in 1952.

title: Young man and kittens, ca. 1919
Lee Carr Durdan preparing taxidermied trophies for Prince Abdorreza Pahlavi, December 17, 1960
description: Transcribed from newspaper caption on back of photograph: "Going to Iran: Lee Carr Durdan, taxidermist at Jonas Brothers here, worked on a mountain goad bagged in British Columbia by Prince Abdorreza Pahlavi of Iran. Jonas Brothers is preparing 40 hunt trophies to ship to the prince, who has returned to Iran after a North American hunting trip. Some of the trophies include, from upper left, a Bighorn sheep from Wyoming, a desert sheep bagged in Nevada, a stone sheep shot in British Columbia, an Alaskan doll sheep and, at lower left, a buffalo bagged in Wyoming." The 1960 City Directory lists the company at 1533 Boylston Ave.

title: Marietta at Playland, ca. 1956
description: Originally constructed in 1931, Playland was in operation for 30 years before closing in 1961. It was located on the site now occupied by the Bitter Lake playfield and Community Center.

title: "Silver Swan" on Lake Union, ca. 1965
description: The "Silver Swan" served as both an excursion boat offering dinner and dancing and a ferry to various Puget Sound locations including, at certain points in its career, Vashon and Kirkland.
photographer: Williamson, Joe D., 1909-1994Williamson's Marine Photo Shop

title: Spring Apartment Hotel at 5th Ave. and Spring St., ca. 1925
description: The building was constructed in 1922. The YWCA appears to its left.

title: Governor-elect Al Rosellini and his wife Ethel, November 8, 1956
description: Transcribed from newspaper caption on back of photograph: "Al Rosellini, Seattle attorney and Democrat, was congratulated by his vivacious wife early Wednesday as it became clear he had been elected governor of Washington. Rosellini ran against Emmett Anderson, Republican candidate. (AP photo)."

title: Puget Sound, ca. 1930Front
description: Postcards spl_shp_41157, spl_shp_41161, and spl_shp_41161-41166 all include notes by Frank Cushman's mother, Carlie E. Doty, on the back.  In some, the photographer is identified as Frank Cushman. It's possible that he is also the photographer of this image but it is not definitive.

title: Coliseum Theater at 5th Ave. and Pike St. after snow, February 2, 1916shp_41258_001
description: Photo taken at 10 p.m. The snowfall on February 2, 1916 totaled 21.5 inches. The Coliseum Theater had opened a little under a month before the snow on January 8, 1916.

title: Portrait of William Bloch's son, ca. 1894Front
description: Portrait of one of William Bloch's sons, most likely William Jr.

title: Portrait of "Miss Germania," ca. 1900Front
description: Portrait of woman identified as Aunt Tillie or "Miss Germania," likely after William Bloch's Germania Café.

title: Fremont Bridge, ca. 1921Front
description: Connecting Fremont and Queen Anne, the Fremont Bridge opened on June 15, 1917. See back of photograph for handwritten description.

Civic Auditorium and Mount Rainier, ca. 1930Front
description: Construction on the Civic Auditorum finished in 1928. Between 1929 and 1930, Seattle Undertook the second phase of the Denny Regrade. Land leveled during this stage can be seen behind the auditorium to the left.

title: Lake Washington Boulevard and Mt. Rainier, Seattle, Wn., ca. 1935front
description: View of Mount Rainier from Lake Washington Boulevard.

title: Physics Hall at the University of Washington, ca. 1950Front
description: Constructed in 1928, the building is now known as Mary Gates Hall. Notes on architecture appear on the back of the postcard.

Columns at the University of Washington, July 16, 1949Front
description: Once located outside of Denny Hall, the columns were moved to their current location in the Sylvan Grove Theater in 1921.

description: View east to Montlake Bridge from ship canal and Montlake cut.
